What is Prompt-a-thon?

Let’s zoom into Prompt-a-thon.

Let me start with a simple question again,
“What’s your current way of solving a problem?” 😄

A: Google
B: Stack Overflow
C: Ask teammate
D: Trial & error
E: All of the above

(“Nice… I’m seeing a lot of ‘E – all of the above’… not surprising 😄
Some Googles, some Stack Overflow… and yeah, asking teammates never fails.”)

“I’m guessing most of us are ‘all of the above’… that’s exactly how we work today.”

“What if instead of doing all this…
you could just ask one well-structured question and get a solid answer in seconds?”

👉 That’s where AI comes in.

“Let’s test this —
Give me a BAD prompt for this task: ‘Summarize a report’”

“😂 These are actually perfect…
‘Summarize this’, ‘Explain fast’… this is exactly how most of us start.”


✅ Better Prompt (Simple & Effective)

Instead of:
❌ “Summarize this”

Use:
✅ “Summarize the following text in 5 bullet points, focusing on key insights, risks, and action items. Keep it concise and clear.”

“And the problem is —
when the prompt is vague, the output is also vague.”

“It’s like asking a teammate:
‘Hey… do this quickly’ —
they’ll come back with something… but maybe not what you wanted.”


“And that’s exactly what Prompt-a-thon is about.”

“Not learning AI theory…
but learning how to ask better questions to get better results.”


So during this challenge,
you’ll move from prompts like ‘summarize this’… 
to prompts that actually give you structured, useful outputs.


This is a hands-on learning challenge designed for all of us to start using AI in our daily work.

You’ll learn how to:

Write effective prompts
Solve real work problems
Improve productivity across development, testing, analysis, and reporting

And the best part —
no prior AI experience is needed.

Why This Matters

Here’s the key idea:

AI is powerful, but the output depends on how you ask.

A small improvement in your prompt can:

Save time
Improve accuracy
Reduce rework

Just like in cricket,
sometimes a small change in timing makes the same shot go from a dot ball to a boundary



